04449nam a22007095i 9789048552566DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485525667 a10.1515/97890485525662doi  a(DE-B1597)611916  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1990-1997 7aCOM0710002bisacsh04a7911 aNg, Jenna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Post-Screen Through Virtual Reality, Holograms and Light Projections :bWhere Screen Boundaries Lie /cJenna Ng. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (282 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMediaMatters0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScreens are ubiquitous today. They display information; present image worlds; are portable; connect to mobile networks; mesmerize. However, contemporary screen media also seek to eliminate the presence of the screen and the visibilities of its boundaries. As what is image becomes increasingly indistinguishable against the viewer’s actual surroundings, this unsettling prompts re-examination about not only what is the screen, but also how the screen demarcates and what it stands for in relation to our understanding of our realities in, outside and against images. Through case studies drawn from three media technologies – Virtual Reality; holograms; and light projections – this book develops new theories of the surfaces on and spaces in which images are displayed today, interrogating critical lines between art and life; virtuality and actuality; truth and lies. What we have today is not just the contestation of the real against illusion or the unreal, but the disappearance itself of difference and a gluttony of the unreal which both connect up to current politics of distorted truth values and corrupted terms of information. The Post-Screen Through Virtual Reality, Holograms and Light Projections: Where Screen Boundaries Lie is thus about not only where the image’s borders and demarcations are established, but also the screen boundary as the instrumentation of today’s intense virtualizations that do not tell the truth. In all this, a new imagination for images emerges, with a new space for cultures of presence and absence, definitions of object and representation, and understandings of dis- and re-placement – the post-screen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aMultimedia systemsxPsychological aspects. 0aPerception (Philosophy). 0aReality. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aCOMPUTERS / Digital Media / Video & Animation.2bisacsh  aScreens, virtual reality (VR), Pepper's Ghost, holograms, projection mapping.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048552566zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048552566423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048552566/original  a978-3-11-074322-7  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK